; conversation-cell.form — a transcript as a content-addressable sequence of utterance cells.
;
; THE ASK (meeting-companion milestone):
;   the agent that sits in a room and listens needs one new artifact it did not have — the
;   conversation itself, as a thing the body can hold, grow, and query. Not prose in a blob, not
;   rows in a database the kernel cannot reach: an ORDERED SEQUENCE of small structured cells, the
;   same on every kernel, content-addressed so a re-sent transcript is recognized rather than copied.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/conversation-cell.fk · proven: tests/conversation-cell-band.fk -> 127)
;
;   An UTTERANCE is the unit cell:  (list ts speaker text-key)
;     ts        — a small-int logical tick (when it was said; a clock, not wall-time).
;     speaker   — a small-int who (0 = human, 1 = agent, 2.. = others in the room).
;     text-key  — a small-int CONTENT ADDRESS standing in for the prose-recipe. The words intern
;                 elsewhere as a R_Block.SEQUENCE of word-cells (prose-as-recipe.form); the
;                 utterance carries the ADDRESS, not the bytes. Same prose -> same key -> same cell.
;
;   A CONVERSATION is a list of utterances, OLDEST FIRST — head is the first thing said, the tail
;   end is the most recent. A transcript is a VALUE you grow with cons and query by walking; no
;   mutation, no store the kernel must reach outside itself.
;
;   The query ops, all pure list walks (no new primitive):
;     cv-append (u conv)         grow at the END — order is the lived order.
;     cv-count  (conv)           how many utterances (len).
;     cv-last   (conv)           the most recent utterance; empty transcript -> the absence value.
;     cv-since  (conv t)         the utterances with ts >= t, INCLUSIVE — selection by each cell's
;                                content, t itself kept, earlier dropped.
;     cv-speaker-said? (conv s)  did speaker s contribute at least one utterance? 1 / 0 — an
;                                existential walk; nobody-said is honest 0, not a fabricated yes.
;
;   THE HEART — content-addressing as dedup:
;     cv-eq? (a b) is EXACT structural equality, leaf-deep: two transcripts are equal when same
;     length and every utterance agrees in lockstep (utt-eq? = three int eq on ts/speaker/text-key).
;     So two transcripts built INDEPENDENTLY from the same utterances in the same order are the
;     SAME cell by structure — a content-addressed store DEDUPS the re-send rather than duplicating
;     it. The band proves it both ways: same content -> equal, one content-key changed -> NOT equal
;     (the address moved). Structure carries identity; equality is a recursion, not a primitive.
;
; THE PROVEN VERDICT — tests/conversation-cell-band.fk -> 127, three-way (Go = Rust = TS), 0 divergent:
;   1  append grows the count (2 -> 3)            ·  2  last is the most recent (u2)
;   4  count is length (3)                         ·  8  since is inclusive (ts>=20 keeps {u1,u2})
;   16 speaker said — yes (the agent contributed)  · 32  speaker said — no (speaker 7 stayed silent)
;   64 content-addressed BOTH ways (same -> equal, changed -> not), so the heart cannot pass by luck.
;
; WHY THIS SHAPE:
;   the transcript is body, not a foreign-runtime record the kernel queries through a bridge. Because
;   it is a value of small ints, the conversation the Mac builds is byte-for-byte the conversation the
;   phone receives, and "is this the same transcript?" is answered by structure on every kernel — the
;   same parity validate.sh checks IS transcript-identity. cv-since / cv-speaker-said? are the first
;   two query doors; new questions are new walks over the same cells, never new control flow.
;
; KIN — the body already holds every piece; this composes them into a transcript:
;   prose-as-recipe.form (the text-key's destination — words as a R_Block.SEQUENCE of word-cells;
;   the utterance addresses it) · federation-addressing.form + merkle.fk (content-addressing across
;   runtimes — cv-eq? is the in-kernel structural twin of that hash-dedup) · sequence-predictor.form
;   (ordered list ops, the same head/tail walk) · turn-taking.form (WHEN the agent adds its voice to
;   this very transcript — the gate; conversation-cell is the record it reads) · cell-recipe-value.form
;   (Recipe/water — a conversation is HOW utterances happen in order; its identity is structural).
;
; LINEAGE:
;   prose-as-recipe.form (the prose layer underneath text-key) · structural-composition.md (list =
;   R_Block.SEQUENCE, one child per element — the discipline a conversation embodies) · the
;   meeting-companion / satsang listener (the first room this transcript holds) · the three-way
;   validate.sh (no trusted prover — parallel kernels agreeing on 127 IS the proof).
